```json
{
"application": "TensorFlow",
"other_software": [
"Horovod",
"Numactl",
"MPI",
"Python",
"Keras",
"SLURM"
],
"resource_requirements": {
"nodes": 1,
"tasks_per_node": 4,
"cores_per_worker": 4,
"intra_threads": 4,
"inter_threads": 1,
"omp_num_threads": 4,
"workers_per_node": 8,
"total_workers": 8,
"time": "1:00:00",
"partition": "test"
}
}
```

This script uses the TensorFlow framework for machine learning with the Horovod library for distributed training. It leverages MPI for inter-node communication and Numactl for memory allocation optimization. The script utilizes SLURM for job submission and resource management, specifying the required nodes, tasks, and time limits. The script further configures the number of threads and affinity settings using OMP_NUM_THREADS and KMP_AFFINITY for optimal performance.

This script appears to be training a 3D Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) model for Ecal energy prediction, utilizing a dataset stored in HDF5 files. The training process involves various parameters, including learning rate, batch size, latent size, and optimizer, as well as a warmup phase for model initialization.
